{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1923"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.32,0.58,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81300"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1923"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"},{"type":"tags","id":"539"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13343"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81300"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman attends her General Practitioner with a three-month history of intermittent right-sided abdominal pain. When it occurs, the pain is constant in nature and lasts about one hour before resolving spontaneously. The pain can sometimes be associated with food and she does not have any other symptoms. She is a recent migrant from Turkey. She has no smoking history and does not drink alcohol. Physical examination is unremarkable with a non-palpable gallbladder. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric colic","Chronic pancreatitis","Biliary colic","Hydatid cyst","Metastatic liver disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA calcified gallstone is visible in the right upper quadrant, inside a distended and thick-walled gallbladder (Image 1). Together with the patient\u0027s clinical picture, this radiological finding would lend support to the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis appearance could easily be mistaken for a cystic lesion, such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst this woman does come from a part of the world where hydatid is endemic, the cysts have a very different appearance. They tend to be thin-walled, have a homogenous appearance and a rim of calcification (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the area of calcification was in the region of the kidneys or ureters, \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric colic\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered as a diagnosis - although the symptoms do not really match for a stone travelling down a ureter. If this was a stone and it was lodged in the renal pelvi-calyceal system, that could explain this patient\u0027s abdominal pain - except that the pain is usually located in the flank.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E, there is upper abdominal pain that worsens after eating, radiating to the back. CT features of chronic pancreatitis that can be visualised on CT scans include dilatation of the main pancreatic duct; calcifications; changes in size, shape, and contour; pseudocysts; and bile duct changes. There is nothing on this CT to suggest such a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E, a CT scan would typically show multiple liver lesions with amorphous calcifications. Calcification may be present with metastases from mucinous gastrointestinal tract tumours and from primary ovarian, breast, lung, renal, and thyroid cancer. Common symptoms include abdominal pain, with the pain occurring near the right shoulder blade or in the upper abdomen. These patients usually have more systemic symptoms such as anorexia and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Only about 75% of gallstones are visible on CT scan"],"references":["Sigmon DF, Dayal N, Meseeha M. Biliary Colic. [Updated 2022 Aug 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Murphy MC, Gibney B, Gillespie C, Hynes J, Bolster F. Gallstones top to toe: what the radiologist needs to know. Insights into Imaging. 2020;11(1):13. Available at: https://insightsimaging.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s13244-019-0825-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1923"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20094"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20679"},{"type":"media","id":"20095"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20094"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6611c773-d153-421e-8468-972259ee00e9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6611c773-d153-421e-8468-972259ee00e9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":413}},{"type":"media","id":"20679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20679"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wow7Z1y3Cb5EyfJJ50SxGMPugVTzNm.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wow7Z1y3Cb5EyfJJ50SxGMPu